  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pipeline success:</strong> Blockbuster approvals in obesity/weight loss (MariTide) or oncology could significantly accelerate top-line growth beyond 5%.</li>
    <li><strong>Acquisition synergies:</strong> The Horizon Therapeutics acquisition could yield better-than-expected cost synergies and revenue growth from Tepezza.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing power:</strong> Better-than-expected pricing environment for newer, highly specialized therapies.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Patent cliffs:</strong> Biosimilar erosion on legacy blockbusters (like Enbrel, Prolia, or Xgeva) could accelerate faster than newer drugs can offset the revenue loss.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory pressure:</strong> The Inflation Reduction Act (IRA) allows Medicare to negotiate drug prices, which could compress margins long-term.</li>
    <li><strong>Pipeline failures:</strong> Late-stage clinical trial failures for highly anticipated drugs (e.g., in obesity) would crush sentiment and expected cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>High debt load:</strong> Amgen carries significant debt (partly from the Horizon acquisition), making it sensitive to sustained high interest rates.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price based on actual cash generation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an 8% discount rate instead of 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Healthcare companies like Amgen generally produce more defensive, recession-resistant cash flows compared to cyclical technology companies. An 8% discount rate reflects this slightly lower risk profile relative to the broader market, while still providing a healthy premium over the 10Y Treasury yield ({treasury10Y}%).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why a 2% terminal growth rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">2% aligns roughly with long-term inflation targets. Pharmaceutical companies constantly fight a "treadmill" effect due to patent expirations. Assuming they can grow significantly faster than the economy forever is aggressive.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

